column2: Grammars for articulating effects, for state machines with strongly typed transitions
column3:
Hi, I'm not familiar with the literature, and my naive searches lead to nothing so far. This may not be a new idea, if it's been experimented with I'd love get pointers. This may also be off base...

A natural extension of typed effects would be to let users articulate grammars. E.G. for file operations, with a RegExp-like syntax, `Open(Read|Write)*Close` would prevent one from writing to a file that hasn't been opened yet (I know there are better ways to enforce this, this is for the sake of the example).

This would enable one to ensure at compile time that a piece of code respects a given protocol (e.g. that you can't write HTTP headers while the body is being sent).

Ported old regression tests to dune

Each file to be tested comes with two dune rules, one for invocation and one that aliases it to `dune runtest`. Rules are autogenerated by `generate_dune_rules.ml` and saved in file `dune.inc`.

Run tests with:
`make test` or `dune runtest`

To add new test case to existing test folders:
- Create test file `text_xyz.eff` and reference file `text_xyz.eff.ref`
- Run `dune runtest` to generate updated `dune.inc` file and `dune promote` to update it


To create a new folder with tests
- Create new folder somewhere under `tests`
- Copy `dune` file from existing test folders and add empty `dune.inc` file. Fix path to `generate_dune_rules` and adjust configurations for new test generation. You can only configure expected exit code for now.
- Add test cases

I'm having a hard time to figuring out, in case the computation is spawning multiple threads, what should happen when one or more of those threads is throwing an exception? If the exception handler is provided after the fork, that feels quite normal, but if the exception handler is provided before the fork, should the thrown exceptions trigger multi-shots of the exception handler ?

I kinda see traditional wisdom is to prevent exceptions from crossing fork boundaries, but that seems guilty for [go statement considered harmful](https://vorpus.org/blog/notes-on-structured-concurrency-or-go-statement-considered-harmful/#go-statement-considered-harmful).

I wonder how this is reasoned with algebraic effects based exception handling, some clue please ?

Btw I don't know either if a `finally` block can be implemented as an effect, and if it can be implemented, I feel it even more subtle to have a multi-shot `finally` block.

On the other hand, I feel the said `goto` semantic of `go` statement can be fixed if exceptions can cross fork boundaries and properly settled.

column2: To imitate algebraic effects with an procedural, interpreted language
column3:
I'd like to have your comment about how much I can imitate algebraic effects with an imperative, interpreted language.

Currently in my mind is a `perform` keyword, prefixing to an expression, so if I resolve function (or procedure, more precise for a procedural language) calls in it, against the call stack, instead of the lexical context of the direct enclosing function/procedure, I kinda feel it implements a sort of algebraic effect call, given the language having pattern matching feature for a calling-site, to dispatch or propagate (to outer frames on the call stack) the effect call.

What's your comment about this idea?

column2: Add mli, move to Symbol and fix type shadowing
column3:
There are three main things in this pull request (in order of commits that fix them):

- Added `.mli` files to most files and got rid of `oldUtils.ml` by inlining unique functions, moving important ones to `coreUtils.ml` and moving important type stuff to `coreTypes.ml`.

- Eff still used `string` for things like type names and field names, so I have completed the move to `Symbol`.

- Eff allowed shadowing of types, so `type a = int;; let (x : a) = 1;; type a = empty;;` produced a value of type `a` which was the `empty` type. Fixed that, wrote tests. 

(And then added some more tests for `pervasives.ml` and copied the new version into `docs/try`)

I extended the language with additional external constants:

- infinity, neg_infinity
- nan

and functions:

- log1p, expm1
- cos, sin, tan
- acos, asin, atan

I also cleaned up _pervasives.ml_ a bit to improve readability.

column2: Loaded code and code displayed are different?
column3:
In the Non-determinism example on the website, the backtrack handler code is written like this
```ocaml
let backtrack = handler
  | effect Decide k ->
    (* We use a second handler to handle the continuation. *)
    handle continue k false with
    | effect Fail _ -> continue k true
;;
```

However, it seems to me, that the paper defines it like follows
```ocaml
let backtrack = handler
  | effect Decide k ->
    (* We use a second handler to handle the continuation. *)
    handle continue k true with
    | effect Fail _ -> continue k false
;;
```

_Notice that the continuations are reversed_

When I try loading the code in the REPL, the handler behaves correctly (I believe), even though the code shown above the REPL is wrong.

I am not sure whether this is a misunderstanding on my side or a bug, but I would be appreciative if someone could take a look at it.

column2: Make syntax compatible with Multicore OCaml
column3:
Ignoring 372 variants (see #30) of Eff floating around, both Eff and Multicore OCaml both offer algebraic effects and handlers with slightly different syntax. I guess there is no syntax so brilliant that it would outweigh the convenience of just taking one source code and putting it into the other language. Since Multicore OCaml is the bigger one here, I suggest Eff adopts their syntax. The necessary changes are

- [x] declare operations with `effect Eff : ...` - we did this some time ago
- [x] call operations with `perform (Eff x)` rather than `#Eff x` - in the long run, we'd also want `perform EffWithNoArgs` and need the type `'a eff`, but in the short run, this just needs some slight changes in the parser
- [x] resume continuations with `continue k x` rather than `k x` - I don't want to make a distinction between functions and continuations, so I suggest to define `continue` as the identity function
- [x] define handling clauses inside a match statement

I don't know whether to keep the old syntax for handlers or not, but maybe I'd issue a warning if it is used as it will make the code incompatible with Multicore OCaml. I would do the same if someone forgot to write `continue` when resuming the continuation. There will always be incompatibilities because OCaml offers so much other stuff, but at least this will give us some guarantees for small effectful examples.

@kayceesrk, @lpw25 - What do you think and did I miss anything?

Equality does not imply the inequality of the types of the expressions that are compared.

eg the inferred type of

```
let f x y = x = y
```

is a -> b -> bool instead of a -> a -> bool

column2: Add an OPAM file for eff.
column3:
This should makes the installation instructions a little simpler.  Once you have OPAM installed you can switch to a suitable OCaml compiler (`opam switch 4.02.1`) and then run

```
opam pin add eff git@github.com:matijapretnar/eff.git
```

to download the dependencies and build and install eff.

column2: missing tutorial style like updated introduction
column3: There is no tutorial/overview comparing the advantages of eff to other ways of describing IO in Ocaml. This would be helpful to discuss the advantages.\n
Ocaml 4.01.0 whines about `or` and wants it replaced with `||`.\n

Expressions with (what would be) recursive types cause the type checker to loop, e.g.

``` ocaml
#type let rec f x = f in f;;
```

column2: Eff 3.0 hangs on handlers which handle invalid operations
column3:
If in pervasives.eff we do this (notice `r#print _ k`):

```
let state r x = handler
  | val y -> (fun _ -> y)
  | r#print _ k -> (fun s -> k s s)
  | r#update s' k -> (fun _ -> k () s')
  | finally f -> f x;;
```

then eff 3.0 hangs.

column2: Tctx functions use global context, pattern exhaust only after infer, merged
column3:
As it turns out, all calls to Tctx.xxxx explicitly passed !Tctx.global, so we might as well use !Tctx.global directly and avoid passing it.

Pattern exhaustion is now performed only after infer succeeds, as it should be.

Merged with upstream.

column2: Checking for non-exhaustive patterns now done only after the inference phase.
column3:
All calls to Tctx.xxx passed !Tctx.global, so I removed the explicit passing of typing contexts.
This means we cannot reason easily in a hypothetical typing context without doing some dirty
work, such as temporarily setting Tctx.global. But this should not create trouble, and the
code is now cleaner.

Pattern exhaustion checking in match statements and checking of irrefutable patterns in
let statements is now done properly after inference succeeds. There might be some uneccesarry
warning regarding the empty type, but this should not create problems in practice.

Review code, and put back in functionality which got deleted:
1. Checks for shadowing of record field labels, constructors and operations. This MUST be done because without such checks we break type safety (the interpreter uses the names at runtime, so when they get shadowed, it finds the wrong ones).
2. Big_int is back, it is just sooo uncool not to have arbitrary-size integers in the 3rd millenium. Also, removing Big_int did not solve any problems. Even with int we cannot use ocaml = and < for comparison because operation instances need custom comparisons.

I also made ?pos mandatory in error reporting (so now it is ~pos). This works well, except for runtime errors, where it would be better not to have a position reported at all.

Pattern exhaustive checks are done badly. They should not be done inside infer, but _after_ infer. This still needs fixed.
Add checks for useless patterns and non-exhaustive pattern lists in match and let expressions. Common.uniq should be fixed to work for lists of big_ints before this is accepted.\n

column2: Got rid of the shell wrapper, better autoconf
column3:
The shell wrapper which looked for rlwrap and ledit is gone, now
eff does this by itself, but only if the interactive shell is
started. Should eff report that a line editor was found?

Makefile.am now declares the eff executable as the main target
(rather than the shell wrapper), as it should. The trick with
settting eff_SOURCES to the empty value is needed, orelse automake
thinks eff is a C program and wants a C compiler.

column2: Resitve nalog iz algoritmov na grafih
column3: Še zadnji sklop rešitev nalog.

Na koncu rešitve je podan postopek odločanja: 

• Če je 0 ≤ p < 3/22, se odločimo za pot preko vozlišča C v list z vrednostjo 0.
• Če je 1/7  ≤ p < 3/22, se odločimo za pot preko vozlišča B.

Mislim, da je v drugem primeru pravi interval: 3/22 ≤  p ≤ 1/4.

V rešitvi je kot iskana vrednost naveden maksimum vsote samo po i-jih: $max(\\sum_{i=1}^{12} j p_{ij} x_{ij}$). Mislim, da bi morala biti vključena še vsota po j-jih: $max(\\sum_{i=1}^{12} (\\sum_{j=1}^3 j p_{ij} x_{ij}))$.\r\n\r\nPrav tako ni naveden pogoj:$\\forall i = 1, \\dots, 12, \\forall j = 1, 2, 3: 0 \\le x_{ij} \\le 1, x_{ij} \\in \\mathbb{Z}$
V rešitvah je pri nalogi 6.3 v tabeli 35 v drugi vrstici (najprej) pri vozlišču a indeks b. Mislim, da bi ustrezen indeks moral biti c.

Pri nalogi 5.43 je napak v navodilu. \r\nV _Tabela 2: Podatki za nalogo 5.43._ je za predmet (oznako) _h_ zadosten pogoj narobe naveden, predmet _h_ je zadosten pogoj za _h_, kar je malo nesmiselno. Vrjetno bi moral biti zadosten pogoj za _g_, saj tako dobim enak rezultat kot je v rešitvah.
#5 Naloga 27
Zdi se mi, da bi morali biti pogoji za spremenljivke $x_i$,$y_i$,$z_i$ podani takole:\r\n$\\forall i \\in \\{ 1,...,n \\} : x_i \\geq 0 , x_i \\in \\mathbb{Z}$,\r\neanko potem tudi za $y_i$ in $z_i$.

The array `[13,6,1,1,6,13]` results unfeasible, yet a graph with the given intersection array exists.
I'm not sure what is meant by the error raised.
The graph comes from the 2-class cyclotomic association scheme of size 13. Hence it is an antipodal 2-cover of $K_{14}$. 
It only has 28 vertices, so I can post its adjacency matrix, if you want to have a look at it.

I can construct a distance regular graph with intersection array `[64,42,1,1,21,64]`.
However, checking the feasibility of those parameters with `drg` yields an `InfeasibleError`.
The error message is `no corresponding 2-design: nonexistence by BCN, Prop. 1.10.5`.
The said proposition is not violated as we have $r = 3$ , $\mu = 21$ and so the equation $kX^2+(-1)^{(r-1)/2} rY^2 = Z^2$ boils down to $64X^2-3Y^2 = Z^2$ which has solutions $X=1, Y=0, Z=8$.

column2: Razpored za jutrišnji kolokvij in izpit
column3:
Ker je omrežje FMF nedosegljivo in tako ne delujejo e-pošta, spletna učilnica in VIS, vam tukaj pošiljam obvestilo glede jutrišnjega kolokvija in izpita. Žal tudi do seznama prijavljenih ne morem, tako da pošiljam vsem, za katere vem, da ste pri predmetu, in imam vaš kontakt na GitHubu. Če veste za koga, ki ga ni med prejemniki, mu prosim posredujte to obvestilo.

Prosim vas, če se razporedite po prvi črki priimka:
* **A** - **P**: predavalnica **2.01**
* **R** - **Ž**: predavalnica **2.04**

Glede na to, da boste lahko pred oddajo izbrali, ali naj se vaš izdelek oceni kot 2. kolokvij ali kot 1. izpit, boste pisali **120 minut**. Tako vas prosim, da ste ob **12:00** v ustrezni predavalnici. Pri sebi boste lahko imeli kalkulator in 2 lista A4 z zapiski. Tabela standardne normalne porazdlitve bo priložena, tako da vam ni treba prinesti svoje.

Ob **14:30** bo sledil še teoretični del izpita. Odvisno od tega, koliko vas bo pisalo, boste bodisi ostali v isti predavalnici, ali pa boste vsi šli v 2.01 (vmes boste seveda imeli prosto). Naj spomnim, da lahko teoretični del opravite tudi na kasnejšem roku (če pa pisnega dela ne opravite, se vem teoretični del ne šteje).

Še to: od jutri do predvidoma 26.6. bo zaprt glavni vhod na Jadransko 21, tako da vstopajte z zadnje strani, pri vratarnici.

Ker se s koncem meseca zaključi projekt ŠIPK, bo treba skupaj s končnim poročilom, ki ga moramo oddati do 3. oktobra, pripraviti tudi javno delujočo različico portala. To pomeni:
* kolikor toliko dodelana grafična podoba (vključno z vsemi aplikacijami, ki bodo vključene)
* vključitev vseh novih oziroma prenovljenih aplikacij v tolikšni meri, da bo objavljeni del dokončan (tj., brez morebitnih nedokončanih funkcionalnosti)
* povezave do delujočih zunanjih aplikacij (@db1456, @zanvd)

Kar še ne bo dokončano do takrat, se lahko vključi naknadno.

Vse torej prosim, da poveste, v kolikšni meri bodo do konca meseca pripravljene vaše aplikacije, da vemo, kaj bomo sedaj vključili.

/CC @AnzeVersnik @Krucifiks @mcafuta

V skladu z navodili za izvajanje (`sipk_lkrv/porocila/Smernice_informiranje & obveščanje.docx` na Dropboxu) moramo na prvo stran portala dati logotipe iz prej omenjene datoteke. @a-l1, prosim te, če jih lahko postaviš na dno prve strani v veji `tablet` (upoštevaj organizacijo iz #3).

S @Krucifiks sva se pogovarjala, da bi bilo dobro preurediti mapo `static`, da ne bo takšne zmede. Predlagam, da se držimo take strukture:

* `css/`: CSS datoteke
    - `plugins/`: CSS datoteke iz knjižnic (trenutno `jquery.jplot.min.css`)
    - ustrezno poimenovane ostale CSS datoteke (mislim, da trenutno ni treba nič preimenovati)
* `images/`: slike
    - `alphabet/`
        + `flags/`
        + `greek/`
        + `sign/`
        + ostale slike, vezane na aplikacijo
    - `substitution/`
    - ustrezno poimenovane mape za ostale aplikacije
    - slike, vezane na celoten izgled
    - slike, ki so (potencialno) uporabne za več aplikacij (puščice, kljukice, itd. - da imamo nek enoten izgled)
* `js/`: JavaScript datoteke
    - `plugins/`: JS datoteke iz knjižnic (JQuery, JQPlot, `md5.js`)
    - `substitution/`
    - ustrezno poimenovane mape ali posamezne datoteke za ostale aplikacije (odvisno od tega, koliko je kode)
    - morebitne skripte, ki jih potrebujemo za celoten portal
* kar je še ostalega (upam, da nič več)

Bom kar sam začel v veji `tablet` (torej z novim dizajnom), in sicer samo s tistim, kar je splošnega za celoten portal. Ostali prosim poskrbite za svojo aplikacijo, pa bomo pridružili, ko bo urejeno. Če ima kdo še kakšne pripombe, naj piše kar sem, da predebatiramo.

CC @AnzeVersnik @db1456 @mcafuta (vas ne vidim, da bi opazovali ta repozitorij)

column2: How to get an isotropic subspace from a bilinear form?
column3:
The vertex set of a dual polar graph is the set of all maximal isotropic subspaces associated to a form. It turns out that this set is more efficiently constructed by finding the orbit of one such subspace under the action of an automorphism group (which is known) than simply filtering all subspaces of the appropriate dimension for isotropic ones. GAP provides the form associated with the automorphism group, but finding a general shape for an isotropic subspace seems a nontrivial task.

I was able to find examples of isotropic subspaces for the forms associated with the symplectic and general unitary groups, so the associated graphs can be constructed more efficiently. In the case of general orthogonal groups, I was only able to find such general constructions for fields in which -1 is a quadratic residue (i.e., binary fields and fields whose order modulo 4 is 1).

So, a way of constructing an isotropic subspace for the missing cases should be found, possibly general enough to cover all cases with an odd characteristic. Ideally, an algorithm for finding a maximal isotropic subspace for a given bilinear form (or quadratic form in the orthogonal case) should be used - in case future versions of GAP choose to use different forms, this would ensure that graphs would still be constructed correctly.
